member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Internal.SequenceJsonCommand.refreshTypeOrders
member.summary: Dictionary of RefreshType orders which defines whether we can group together one Refresh command followed by another Refresh command. The rule is: - any RefreshType not present in list cannot be grouped with anything else and have to be executed in its own sequence point - RefreshType of order X can follow RefreshType of order less than or equal to X. (Order is not decreasing.) Example: ClearValues + DataOnly + Calculate can be grouped in single batch ClearValues + DataOnly + ClearValues cannot be grouped in single batch (sequence point is required before 2nd ClearValues)

member.name: M:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Extensions.ToJsonCase(System.String)
member.summary: Extension method that converts C# identifier to match Json naming convention
member.returns: Identifier in Json style (camel case)
member.remarks: Conversion to camel case is really simple under the assumption that input identifier is in Pascal case. https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/vstudio/ms229043(v=vs.100).aspx If identifier is 3 or more characters long, just make 1st letter lowercase. If identifier is 2 or less characters long, just make identifier lowercase. There is a problem through with 2-letters uppercase identifiers like "ID". "ID" will be converted to "id". But then conversion back to C# (Pascal) case is ambiguous. Should it become "Id" or "ID" ? For this reason this method does not support such identifiers.

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.GenericLinkBasedObjectComparer`1
member.summary: Generic comparer of MetadataObjects that embraces identity of MetadataObject based on its cross-link to another object and possibly some additional property
member.typeparam: Type of metadata objects being compared
member.remarks:
Imagine you have two collections of metadata objects ('A' and 'B') and you want to compare them to identify which objects are same and which ones are different. (This problem arises when user say does model.Sync() and we need to match object tree coming from Server with 'model' object tree to update 'model' tree in place.) Here you need to establish an identity of the object to be able to answer question: "does reference X points to same object as reference Y". You basically need to derive 'identity' from reference.
Depending on the collection, you do it differently. For named collection like Tables, it's enough to compare object names, i.e. identity is based on object name. For ObjectTranslations, identity should be based on a pair of object that is being translated plus translated property, i.e. objTr.Object+objTr.Property. (If ObjectTransactions X and Y provide a translation for same property of same object, they essentially match.) For PerspectiveXxx objects, identity should be based on the master objects, i.e. references to Xxx object. (If PerspectiveColumns X and Y point to same Column object, it means they match.)
GenericLinkBasedObjectComparer does comparison based on a cross-link (like objTr.ObjectID) which is called "identity link" and maybe additional property (like objTr.Property), such that it can help with known unnamed collections.
Comparison of cross-links ("whether link A and link B point to same object") is done in one of two ways: - Based on ID This happens when affected objects returned by the server are merged with object tree on client, links inside affected objects will always have IDs those links may be unresolved (because target object is not present in affected objects rowset). - Based on object path This happens for normal user copy of one object tree into another one.

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.JsonObjectTreeSchemaWriter
member.summary: Helper class for writing a JSON schema of an object tree.
member.remarks: This class outputs the schema of the structure of the object tree, but caller of this class can customize which properties are allowed for this object by schema. The most common use of this class is to create a schema for an ObjectTranslations collection. JSON for ObjectTranslations collection partially mirrors the object tree of the objects being translated, plus for every translated objects it may contain "translatedCaption" / "translatedXxx" property. See JsonObjectTreeWriter.

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ObjectLinkBase`2
member.summary: Represents an ObjectID-based link between objects in TOM tree. TOM objects are organized in a tree-like structure, and can have references (links) to each other. In DDL rowsets, links are represented as "ID of an referenced object". For example, Column object has links to Table (as "TableID" field) and to AttributeHierarchy (as "AttributeHierarchyID" field). This class contains logic to support links based on object Ids. Basic operations are: assign Id, assign Object, resolve link
member.typeparam: Type of object that hold a reference to another object
Type of object that is being referenced

member.name: M:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ObjectLinkBase`2.IsEqualTo(Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ObjectLinkBase{`0,`1},Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyContext)
member.summary: Checks whether 'this' link is same as 'other' link in a sense that links point to same object.
member.remarks: This method is called in a context of copying one subtree into another subtree. Say we're copying object B from one subtree into object A from another subtree (B -> A). We're comparing B's body to A's body (body contents include regular properties and links). If bodies are found to be different, then: - new body is created for A - new body is marked as belonging to Modified savepoint, - new body's content is copied from B's body This allows later to quickly go through bodies touched in Modified savepoint, compare them with prev body and get delta. If bodies are found to be equal, nothing happens. Object A is treated as not changed.
member.param: CopyContext whose Flags give additional hints whether link targets should be considered same object or different objects
member.returns: True, if links differ from each other, False otherwise

member.name: M:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ObjectLinkBase`2.IsEqualTo(Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ObjectLinkBase{`0,`1})
member.summary: Checks whether 'this' link is same as 'other' link in a sense that links point to same object
member.remarks: This method is called in a context of comparing two bodies of the same object to figure out delta between them
member.returns: True, if links differ from each other, False otherwise

member.name: M:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CrossLink`2.SerializeToJsonObject(System.Boolean,System.String,Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ObjectType,Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.JsonObject,System.Int32,System.Boolean)
member.summary: Serializes current CrossLink as a part of given Json object using
member.param: An indication of the json style to use
Type of object that stands at the beginning of the emitted object path
Output Json object in form of Dictionary string -> object
member.remarks:
CrossLink will be written into provided Json object as one or more properties with prefix For example, cross link FromEndColumn in Relationship object pointing to column Foo in table Bar will be written as : "propNameTable" : "Bar" "propNameColumn" : "Foo"
In given example, Table and Column names represent what is called "object path" - names of objects that would need to be visited when traversing from root to target object. Root can be a Model (in which case object path is called absolute) or some other object (in which case object path is called relative).
For example, Column.SortedBy cross-link always points to column in same table. So it's enough to use relative path { column: Bar } to identify target column. On the opposite, CalculatedTableColumn.ColumnOrigin always points to column in different table, so path containing both Table and Column is needed.
Caller has to decide which object should act as root of traversal and pass this info in pathTopObjectType parameter.

member.name: M:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.MetadataObject.GetNameLinkedObjects(System.String)
member.summary: When overwritten by objects like Table, Column, Measure, or Hierarchy, whose name is sourced to other objects, returns the sequence of PerspectiveXxx or TablePermission objects that point to this object.
member.param: Name of this object that has to be considered.
member.returns: Sequence of objects that derived name from this object.
member.remarks:
Because PerspectiveXxx collections index objects by name, it's more efficient to search for PerspectiveXxx objects by name rather than references. For example, p.PerspectiveTables[c.Table.Name].PerspectiveColumns[c.Name] will be more efficient than p.PerspectiveTables.SingleOrDefault(pt => pt.Table == c.Table) .PerspectiveColumns.SingleOrDefault(pc => pc.Column == c) Consider use cases where we want to lookup perspective objects immediately after renaming an object. PerspectiveXxx objects will already have a new name, but collections retain the old name in the index. For objectName, the caller can pass an old name that can still be used in lookup.
A similar logic applies to the TablePermission collection, for Role objects.

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ObjectChangeTracker
member.summary: ObjectChangeTracker static class acts as a single place reacting on modifications being made to metadata object tree It's being called when tree is about to change: objects are being added/removed from the tree, or objects' properties change Currently it does few things: - creates new savepoint if it detects changes on 'Synced' savepoint - associates modified/added/removed object with latest savepoint - if object's Name or Id are being changed, notifies parent collection, such that parent collection can update indicies In the future it can be used to do various validations of model modifications. For example, when measure's name is being changed, it can verify uniqueness of name across the model. Or if column is being removed from the model, it can validate that no relationhips remain that reference the column being removed

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ObjectPath
member.summary:
Represents an object path. Object path is a way to uniquely identify an object within a model. For example, if we want to uniquely identify a column, we can say: "column Foo from table Bar". Because there is only one table Bar in a model and only one column Foo in that table, column is uniquely described. So object path literally means a path from root of the tree (Model) to individual node (metadata object) through other nodes. For this reason, path is represented by a list of pairs: ObjectType and ObjectName.
Not that path can be either full (starts from root) or relative (starts from other object) Full path is used, for example, to describe FromColumn field in a Relationship object when serializing Relationship into Json or when sending definition of relationship object to a Server. Relative path is used when referencing object sits close to the object being referenced. For example, Column has a field SortedBy which refers to a column in same table. For this reason, column which is pointed by SortedBy field is described using shorter path: Column : Foo Instead of: Table: Bar Column: Foo
Currently all objects that we reference (Table, DataSource, Column, etc) have paths that consists of named objects only. For this reason, in pair (ObjectType, ObjectName) ObjectName is always non-empty If future, we may need to reference unnamed objects, like KPIs, and then object path may look like: Table: Bar Measure: Foo KPI :

member.summary: The user-specified name for the column. Required for calculated columns and columns bound to data. Columns in calculated tables can leave this unspecified if the name can be inferred from the expression.

member.summary: Specifies the auto-generated name for the column. It is valid only for columns of the type CalculatedTableColumn.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.ExplicitDataType
member.summary: User-specified data type to be enforced on the contents of the column. Values include: Automatic (1), String (2), Int64 (6), Double (8), DateTime (9), Decimal (10), Boolean (11), Binary (17), and Unknown (19). Automatic is used to automatically infer the data type of a calculated column or a column in a calculated table. Unknown cannot be set on the ExplicitDataType field. Instead, it is set automatically by the engine on the InferredDataType field of a calculated column that is in a semantic error state.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.InferredDataType
member.summary: Specifies the engine-generated data type for this column. It is valid only for columns of the type CalculatedTableColumn or Calculated.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.DataCategory
member.summary: Specifies the type of data contained in the column so that you can add custom behaviors based on column type. There are 248 possible values. The first ten are Invalid (-1), All (1), Regular (2), Image (3), ImageBMP (4), ImageGIF (5), ImageJPG (6), ImagePNG (7), ImageTIFF (8), ImageURL (9), Id (10). For the rest, please refer to the MS-SSAS-T SQL Server Analysis Services Tabular Protocol documentation on MSDN.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.Description
member.summary: The description of the column, visible to developers at design time and to administrators in management tools, such as SQL Server Management Studio.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.IsHidden
member.summary: A boolean value that indicates whether a column is treated as hidden by client visualization tools. True if the column is treated as hidden; otherwise false.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.State
member.summary: Enumerates the state of the column. Possible values include the following. Ready (1) The column is queryable and has up-to-date data. NoData (3) The column is queryable but has no data. This state is applicable only to columns of the type Data. CalculationNeeded (4) The column is not queryable and needs to be refreshed (that is, recalculated) to become functional. This state applies only to columns of the type Calculated or CalculatedTableColumn. SemanticError (5) The column is in an error state because of an invalid expression. The column is not queryable. This state applies only to columns of the type Calculated or CalculatedTableColumn. EvaluationError (6) The column is in an error state because of an error during expression evaluation. The column is not queryable. This state applies only to columns of the type Calculated or CalculatedTableColumn. DependencyError (7) The column is in an error state because some of its calculation dependencies are in an error state. The column is not queryable. This state applies only to columns of the type Calculated or CalculatedTableColumn. Incomplete (8) Some parts of the column have no data, and the column needs to be refreshed to bring the data in. The column is queryable. This state applies only to columns of the type Data. SyntaxError (9) The column is in an error state because of a syntax error in its expression. The column is not queryable. This state applies only to columns of the type Calculated.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.IsUnique
member.summary: A boolean value that indicates whether the column contains only unique values. True if the values are unique; otherwise false.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.IsKey
member.summary: A boolean value that indicates whether the column is a key of the table. True if the column is a key of the table; otherwise false.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.IsNullable
member.summary: If false, the column cannot contain nulls. Even if true, it may still not allow nulls if it's a key column.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.Alignment
member.summary: Specifies the text alignment of the column in report visualizations. The possible values are Default (1), Left (2), Right (3), Center (4).

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.TableDetailPosition
member.summary: Determines whether you can place this column in the DefaultDetails collection of the Table. This collection is an ordered set of Column types. A positive value indicates participation in the collection. The collection is sorted in ascending order of this element. The DefaultDetails collection is returned as part of the CSDL metadata returned by the DISCOVER_CSDL_METADATA operation.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.IsDefaultLabel
member.summary: A boolean value that indicates whether this column is included in the DisplayKey element in CSDL.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.IsDefaultImage
member.summary: A boolean value that indicates whether this column is returned as the DefaultImage property in CSDL.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.SummarizeBy
member.summary: A value indicating the default function, if any, used to aggregate this field. The possible values are Default (1), None (2), Sum (3), Min (4), Max (5), Count (6), Average (7), DistinctCount (8). If unspecified, Default is assumed for numeric fields, None for all other fields.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Column.Type
member.summary: Specifies the data binding. Values include Data (1) where the contents of this column come from a DataSource, Calculated (2) where the contents are computed from an expression after the Data columns have been populated, RowNumber (3) where the column is an internal column representing the row number, or CalculatedTableColumn (4) where tables that are based on a calculated expression will automatically infer and generate the columns in the table.

NoData (3): The partition is queryable but has no data. This state applies only to partitions with a type other than Calculated. CalculationNeeded (4): The partition is not queryable and needs to be refreshed (that is, recalculated) to become functional. This state applies only to partitions of the type Calculated. SemanticError (5): The partition is in an error state because of an invalid expression and is not queryable. This state applies only to partitions of the type Calculated. EvaluationError (6): The partition is in an error state because of an error during expression evaluation. The partition is not queryable. This state applies only to partitions of the type Calculated. DependencyError (7): The partition is in an error state because some of its calculation dependencies are in an error state. The partition is not queryable. This state applies only to partitions of the type Calculated. Incomplete (8): Some parts of the partition have no data, and the partition needs to be refreshed to bring the data in. The partition is queryable. This state applies only to partitions of a type other than Calculated. SyntaxError (9): The partition is in an error state because of a syntax error in its expression. The partition is not queryable. This state applies only to partitions of the type Calculated.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Partition.Type
member.summary: The type of partition. Possible values are as follows. Query (1): The data in this partition is retrieved by executing a query against a DataSource. Calculated (2): The data in this partition is populated by executing a calculated expression. None (3): The source is undefined. Data can come from pushed data or from out of line bindings that pull in data from an explicitly specified data source.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Partition.Mode
member.summary: Defines the method for making data available in the partition. Possible values are as follows. Import (0) Data will be imported from a data source. DirectQuery (1) Data will be queried dynamically from a data source. Default (2): Only partitions can use this value. When set, the partition will inherit the DefaultMode of the Model. Push (3): Data will be pushed into the partition. The Mode of a Partition can be set to Default (2), in which case it will inherit its Mode from the DefaultMode of the Model

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Partition.DataView
member.summary: Determines which partitions should be selected to run queries against the model. The possible values are as follows. Full (0) - Partitions with DataView set to Default or Full are selected. Sample (1): Partitions with DataView set to Default or Sample are selected. SampleAndFull (2): All partitions are selected. Default (3) - Inherits from the default DataView of the Model object.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.TablePermission.State
member.summary: Provides information on the state of the permission. Possible values and their interpretation are as follows. Ready (1) The permission has a valid expression. NoData (3) Not applicable. CalculationNeeded (4) Not applicable. SemanticError (5) The expression of the TablePermission object has a semantic error. EvaluationError (6) Not applicable. DependencyError (7) A dependency associated with this TablePermission object is in an error state (SemanticError, EvaluationError, or DependencyError). Incomplete (8) Not applicable. SyntaxError (9) The TablePermission object is in an error state because of a syntax error in its expression. The TablePermission object is not queryable. This state applies only to TablePermission objects of the type Calculated.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.TablePermission.ErrorMessage
member.summary: A string that explains the error state associated with the current object. It is set by the engine only when the state of the object is one of these three values: SemanticError, DependencyError, or EvaluationError.

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.PropertyFlags
member.summary: Flags associated with MetadataObject's property

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.PropertyFlags.None
member.summary: None of the flags are set

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.PropertyFlags.Ddl
member.summary: Property is present in DDL schema of the MetadataObject (directly serialized from/to DDL) This flag is set for properties like "Column.ExplicitDataType", "Column.Description", but not for "Column.DataType" or "Column.IsDataTypeInferred"

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.PropertyFlags.User
member.summary: Property is public and available for user. It may or may not be directly serialized from/to DDL. This flag is set for properties like "Column.DataType", "Column.IsDataTypeInferred", "Column.Description", but not for "Column.ExplicitDataType"

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.PropertyFlags.ReadOnly
member.summary: Property is read-only. User can't change it explicitly. If it's changed by metadataObject.CopyFrom(otherMetadataObject), it won't be sent to the server

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.PropertyFlags.DdlAndUser
member.summary: Property is both public and is directly serialized to/from DDL

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.PropertyFlags.Json
member.summary: Property is of string type and contains JSON content.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.PropertyFlags.ModelReference
member.summary: Property is a reference in the model object. The model changes are usually sent as an 'special' Alter command before any other changes; however, because the reference may be pointing to an object created in the same change then those changes need to be serialized as part of the regular Alter post the Create\Delete commands of the batch

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ITxObject
member.summary: Interface representing an object whose state can be tracked at multiple points of time using save points. Essentially, such an object can have a history of states, each belonging to a different savepoint. An object can be compared to any of its previous states or reverted to a previous state. Currently this interface is implemented by metadata objects and metadata object collections.

member.summary: Head of object bodies chain, each body representing object state at different points of time

member.summary: Creates a body object with default properties.

member.summary: Notifies ITxObject that its Body was reverted by TxManager.

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ITxObjectBody
member.summary:
Interface representing a body of object whose state can be tracked at multiple points of time. Essentially, it's a body who defines the state of the object, and object is just a get/set wrapper on top of it. ITxObject can have multiple chained ITxObjectBodies which belong to different savepoints. As an example:
ITxObject ^ | ITxObjectBody -- ITxObjectBody -- ITxObjectBody -- ITxObjectBody (Savepoint 3) (Savepoint 2) -- (Savepoint 1) -- (Savepoint 0 - initial state of object)

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ITxObjectBody.Owner
member.summary: Object who owns this body.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ITxObjectBody.CreatedFrom
member.summary: Previous body object in body chain. Previous body represents earlier state of the object than current body.

member.name: P:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ITxObjectBody.Savepoint
member.summary: Savepoint to which body belongs to.

member.name: M:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ITxObjectBody.CopyFrom(Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.ITxObjectBody,Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyContext)
member.summary: Copies body properties from another body. CopyContext.Flags allows to specify which properties gets copied (i.e. inferred properties are ignored, etc). (Both bodies are supposed to represent same object type. I.e. you can't copy Column body to Table body.)

member.summary: Reverts all objects to a state they were in at given savepoint

member.name: M:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.TxManager.CreateInitialSavepointsForModel(Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.Model,System.Boolean,System.Boolean)
member.summary: Creates initial set of savepoints for the Model that does not have them yet.
member.param: True, if BeginTx has to be the first savepoint; False, if Synced has to be the first savepoint
True, if Model exists on Server and is in sync with Server; False, if Model is new
member.remarks: Few examples of when initial savepoints have to be created: 1. Initial loading of Model from the Server createBeginTx == false, modelIsSynced = true Will create savepoints: Synced 2. Database.set_Model OR Server.Databases.Add(new Db with existing Model) a) inside transaction createBeginTx == true, modelIsSynced == false Will create savepoints: BeginTx -> Synced -> Modified b) outside transaction createBeginTx == false, modelIsSynced == false Will create savepoints: Synced -> Modified

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.TxSavepoint

member.summary: Flags used to copy or clone the branch of a Tabular metadata object tree.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.UserCopy
member.summary: This flag is used when the user copies an object using a public-facing API, such as Model.CopyFrom(Model otherModel).

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.IncludeObjectIds
member.summary: Objects IDs to be copied or cloned.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.CloningBody
member.summary: A Copy or Clone operation is performed in the context of cloning the object body. A Metadata object can have a chain of bodies that represent state of the object at different points in time.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.DontTrackObjectChanges
member.summary: A Copy or Clone operation is performed without tracking object changes and without registering changed objects in the current savepoint. This occurs when object body is being cloned.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.Incremental
member.summary: Copies only incremental changes from one tree into another.
member.remarks: This occurs in the context of applying Server changes (AffectedObjects) to the Client. AffectedObjects form one or more subtrees that are incrementally copied into a Model tree on the Client. An example of an incremental copy is copying one object collection to another, where new objects are copied from the first collection to the second, preserving any non-impacted objects in the second collection, under the assumption that the first collection contains only incremental changes.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.ShallowCopy
member.summary: Copies only top-level object without copying children objects. Links are left unresolved.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.IgnoreIdsForChildLinks
member.summary: Ignore IDs when comparing child links. With this flag, childLink1.Object and childLink2.Object are considered to be the same objects (as long as they're not null) even if their IDs are different. This flag is not set in scenarios like Model.Sync(), where we do care if say a Measure's KPI object was replaced with another KPI object (in which case childLink1.ID != childLink2.ID, so we recognized it as KPI was replaced). This flag can be used in scenario of comparing one deployed Model to another deployed Model, where we care about Models being semantically the same, even if Server assigned different IDs to objects.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.DontResolveCrossLinks
member.summary: Normally when a subtree is copied from another subtree (in Model.Clone() or Model.CopyFrom(Model other) scenarios), we want to fix cross-links because they're pointing to objects from source tree after the copy. With this flag set, cross-links will not be fixed. This flag is used in ApplyImpact logic because it resolves cross-links in some custom fashion.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.IgnoreInferredProperties
member.summary: Don't copy properties that are inferred by Server, such as Column.State This flag is used when user calls Model.CopyFrom(otherModel), because with everything that touches inferred properties/objects only Server can say what the value will be, so we expect user to eventually do Model.SaveChanges() after Model.CopyFrom(otherModel). This flag is not used in scenario of Model.Sync() or Model.ApplyServerImpact(), because at that moment the 'otherModel' is coming from Server and it is known to have consistent state.

member.name: F:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyFlags.IgnoreInferredObjects
member.summary: Don't create or delete objects that are inferred by Server, such as RowNumber column or AttributeHierarchy This flag is used when user calls Model.CopyFrom(otherModel), because with everything that touches inferred properties/objects only Server can say what the value will be, so we expect user to eventually do Model.SaveChanges() after Model.CopyFrom(otherModel). This flag is not used in scenario of Model.Sync() or Model.ApplyServerImpact(), because at that moment the 'otherModel' is coming from Server and it is known to have consistent state.

member.name: T:Microsoft.AnalysisServices.Tabular.CopyContext
member.summary: Context of the operation of copying a Tabular object subtree to another subtree. It's the list of original objects mapped to new objects created by the copy or clone operation.

member.summary: Validates links from one object to another. It can be a parent link, child link, or cross link.
member.param: Object containing the link. For example, in a Relationship.FromColumn link, the link owner is the Relationship object.
Name of the property in the owner object that is backed by the link. For example, in aRelationship.FromColumn link, the property is the "FromColumn".
Object that is referenced by the link. For example, in a Relationship.FromColumn link, the target object is the Column object.
Path of the object referenced by the link. For example, in a Relationship.FromColumn link, the target path might be { Table: "X", Column: "Y"})
A ValidationResult object that will be populated with validation errors if they exist.
True if TomValidationException must be thrown instead of populating ValidationResult, False otherwise.
member.remarks:
Depending on the value of throwOnError, this method either throws TomValidationException or adds the validation error to ValidationResult.
The link does not have to be valid to be in scope. Specifically, an unresolved link might have a null targetObj and a non-null targetPath.
